{"key":"processedPost-9407783","value":{"id":9407783,"first":9406398,"last":9407863,"when":1228953665,"utime":"12/11/08 02:01 AM","content":"Unless the lids seal airtight, you don't need holes.&nbsp; You'll get gas exchange from around the edges.<br /><br />The statement that the holes need to be even with the substrate is incorrect.&nbsp; The mycelium will produce heat as it grows, and this will in turn cause turbulence that will push the CO2 around and out whatever openings are there.<br /><br />It really makes little difference if you protect the sides from light or not.&nbsp; The mycelium doesn't just pin where light hits it.&nbsp; Air exchange is the number 1 pinning trigger, so once the substrate pulls away from the edges, it will side-pin whether you cover them or not.&nbsp; Even black trays will side pin. <br />RR","title":"Re: New Tray Air Holes ??","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}